    <div class="row featurette">
      <div class="col-md-4">
        <h1> Memories of the Dirty War </h1>
  <p>
  
    The best part of this experience was that we sort of just happened upon it. Sam vaguely recalled reading about a holiday on this weekend, but nothing specific. Then we found the downtown so packed with people that the driver couldn’t get closer than a 15-minute walk to our hotel. 
    
    “Impossible!” the driver cried, helpless to get us within about a half-dozen blocks from the hotel. But we reassured him we were okay to walk. No biggie, we can just hoof it, we decide.
    
    Make a mental note for future travel, when you wish for a hotel in the middle of everything, you can indeed get it. And it was pretty awesome.
    
    People were sharing some strong, emotional connections that day, and there was absolutely nowhere else we wanted to be, once we found it. When they unfurled a tapestry with the faces of the disappeared, the significance was like a blow to the chest, its deafening significance. Fascism is a word we use a lot in the U.S. media and in our conversations about the nation. But we don’t really know it. In the Buenos Aires streets that day, it felt impossible to know it like these people did, to understand the fear of fascism the way these people do.
    
    And it makes me very afraid.
    
    
  
  </p>

      </div>
      <div class="col-md-8">

        
        <div class="container">

            <iframe src="https://summerlin.media/Argentina_2023_2.html" width="100%" height="575"></iframe>

        </div>
  


      </div>
    </div>

  
    <div class="row featurette">


<p>
  A festival of remembrance, of those who disappeared under the military dictatorship of Argentina in the 70s and 80s. A dark origin, but it has become a celebration of the people passed, and the people who remain. 30-some-thousand people disappeared from Argentina during this period. When we asked, the locals would tell us, too. They would make sure we know.
    
  It's ever so erie, to be in a nation with such a recent memory of fascist violence.
  
  To see this vibrant celbration, people packed in around the obelisk, it was a moving mixture of feelings, of joy and resolute passion. I heard a story about the Argentina military government dumping bodies at the base of the obelisk, an image of terror.
  
  The dancers unfurl a blue tapestry checkered with photos of the disappeared. This was their tribute, to ensure we do not forget the names and the faces.
  
  Racial hatred feels more understood, resource fighting feels more understood, Religious persecution feels like a known evil.
  
  But this fear of pure, authoritarian power seems perhaps darker still, and so unknown to us. And those who've seen it almost tell us with their stares, "It will happen to you, too."
  
  
  
  General festive chaos reigned across these many square blocks around the Obelisco.
  
  Among the densely packed crowds, the smell of street foods rise in smoke from vendors grills. The streets were scattered with debris. One narrow street corridor stank of piss, where men, and at least one woman we saw, were urinating in the small privacy offered by a dumpster. 
  
  What immediately comes to mind is a couple years before, in an Irish bar in Killarney, a group of Harley Davidson-clad Irishmen from Belfast, became incredibly solemn, singing Zombie by the Cranberries.
  
  The classic 90s grunge song about the times of the Troubles in Ireland, a time of violence and destruction between the Republic of Ireland and the British-controlled Northern Ireland. One of the men says they are from Belfast. “A proud Irishman,” he says.
  
  To meet people in such an intimate space inspires a deep sense of privilege.

</p>

    </div>

