    <div class="row featurette">
      <div class="col-md-4">
        <h1> Mountain refuge </h1>
  
        <p>

          The mountains were, of course, wide open spaces. Driving along, I would almost well up in tears in joy at the expanding space around me, and long deep breath of relief at not seeing another person around.
          
          Mountains of legendary name, Patagonia, Fitz Roy.
          
          And El Chaltan was, of course, a radically different environment from Buenos Aires. In the middle of nowhere, in a deep flat desert around Lago Argentina, the small mountain town at the base of Mt. Fitzroy. As we approached in the night, we saw not a single light on the landscape until we were within a couple miles of the town.
           
          There’s clearly plenty of money coming through this place. Comparison to Buenos Aires is just impossible.
          
          The restaurants are small. This is the homebase from one of the most icon trekking in the world. Patagonia.
          
          The tiny town has been in the Argentine news lately, as the home of the country’s vice president, Christina Fernandez Kirchner. Just a few months before she withstood an assassination attempt, and the Argentine news is filled with headlines of corruption investigations into her. Recently she’s vowed not to run for re-election in the upcoming national election.
          
          Of course, the allure of the mountains is intoxicating and reminded me a lot of earlier years in Colorado mountain towns.
          
          The modern tragedy of the two worlds living side by side, the two worlds of squalor and riches. The modern hope of communal joy growing from sheer darkness.
          
          After a couple days of hiking and climbing, our guide said that we had been very lucky with the calm weather. We didn’t know at first what he meant, but on the third day the wind did indeed kick up. I can’t imagine trying to hike or climb in that wind, with the intense projectile danger from hurtling sand. 
          
        </p>
  
  
      </div>
